<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
The wall's not a bad idea.  But then there's balance issues and grief issues:<P>1) Balance - A Sorcerer casting 17 walls one right after the other in front of a keep door just specifically to keep the enemy from *ever* getting up there.<P>2) Grief - An irritated Sorcerer builds walls around the enterances to various highly-populated areas in an effort to piss people off and keep them from going where they want to.<P>As for |3ullseye's idea, it actually isn't a bad one.  Granted, lag would be horrid.  But as far as usefullness, it is indeed greatly useful.  First, to keep Archers from targetting (wow, an anti-archer ability!  First one, too), second to cancel spells (1 5 dmg per tick might actually stop a few heals or fireballs, if the casters are silly enough to remain standing in the cloud).  Strategic value is also there, as clouds would be useful in keep the enemy away from a location that you don't want them in.<P>To be able to use the spell properly, one would have to make it so that it is location-targetted.  It wouldn't be quite as useful if you had to target a person for the cloud.  But if it was location-oriented, then there'd be misuse.  People would leave clouds in shops and stuff.<P>(random idea, what about a cloud that covers only the Sorcerer?  It would protect them from direct archer fire, though not from AE spells)<P>~Sigma<BR>27 Sorcerer<BR>Percival
</FONT>
